Phenyl groups can increase the melting point due to their ability to stack in a solid state, which enhances intermolecular attractions; let's estimate this enhancement to be +30°C for each ring. Next, the benzylidene (-CH=) bridge between the oxazole ring and the phenyl ring may further rigidify the structure, potentially increasing the melting point. We'll assign a modest increase of +10°C for this moiety. The 1,3-oxazole contributes significantly to the rigidity and ability for hydrogen bonding, which would substantially raise the melting point; we will estimate an increase of +50°C for this heterocycle. Added up, the total estimated increase is +30 (phenyl) + 30 (phenyl) + 10 (benzylidene) + 50 (oxazole) over benzene.
Prediction: 5.5 (base melting point for benzene) + 30 (first phenyl) + 30 (second phenyl) + 10 (benzylidene) + 50 (1,3-oxazole) = 125.5°C
